# Skill Exchange Request Feature Implementation Plan

The goal is to implement a feature that allows users to request skills from other users and manage these requests (accept/reject), as per the user stories.

## Proposed Changes

### Model & Repository
#### [NEW] `com.skillshare.skillshare.model.exchange.ExchangeRequestStatus.java`
- Enum representing the request status: `PENDING`, `ACCEPTED`, `REJECTED`, `COMPLETED`.

#### [NEW] `com.skillshare.skillshare.model.exchange.ExchangeRequest.java`
- JPA Entity containing:
  - `Long id`
  - `User requester` (ManyToOne)
  - `User skillOwner` (ManyToOne)
  - `Skill selectedSkill` (ManyToOne)
  - `String message` (Optional)
  - `ExchangeRequestStatus status`
  - `Instant createdAt`, `Instant updatedAt`
  - Proper constraints to prevent duplicate requests (requester, skillOwner, selectedSkill combination).

#### [NEW] `com.skillshare.skillshare.repository.ExchangeRequestRepository.java`
- Spring Data JPA Repository for `ExchangeRequest`.
- Methods to find by `requester` and `skillOwner`.
- Method to check if a pending/accepted request already exists for a specific user, owner, and skill.

### DTOs
#### [NEW] `com.skillshare.skillshare.dto.exchange.ExchangeRequestCreateDTO.java`
- DTO containing `skillId`, `message`.

#### [NEW] `com.skillshare.skillshare.dto.exchange.ExchangeRequestResponseDTO.java`
- DTO returning request details (id, requester name, skill owner name, skill name, message, status, createdAt).

### Services
#### [NEW] `com.skillshare.skillshare.service.exchange.ExchangeRequestService.java`
- Service interface and implementation for handling business logic:
  - `createRequest(Long requesterId, ExchangeRequestCreateDTO dto)`
    - Validates skill exists and belongs to someone else.
    - Prevents duplicates.
  - `getIncomingRequests(Long skillOwnerId)`
  - `getOutgoingRequests(Long requesterId)`
  - `acceptRequest(Long requestId, Long skillOwnerId)`
  - `rejectRequest(Long requestId, Long skillOwnerId)`
  - `completeRequest(Long requestId, Long userId)` (updates status to COMPLETED if user is participant)

### Web Controllers & Routing
#### [NEW] `com.skillshare.skillshare.controller.web.ExchangeRequestWebController.java`
- Handles routing for requests management:
  - `GET /requests` (Dashboard to show sent and received requests)
  - `POST /requests/create`
  - `POST /requests/{id}/accept`
  - `POST /requests/{id}/reject`
  - `POST /requests/{id}/complete`

### Views (Thymeleaf)
#### [MODIFY] [src/main/resources/templates/browse-skills.html](file:///c:/Users/jadav/Desktop/SE_Project/Skill-Share/Skill-Share/src/main/resources/templates/browse-skills.html)
- Add a "Request Exchange" button to each skill (excluding the user's own skills).
- Add a modal or form to submit the request with an optional message.

#### [NEW] `src/main/resources/templates/exchange-requests.html`
- A new page with two sections/tabs:
  - "Received Requests": Lists incoming requests with options to Accept/Reject (if PENDING) or Mark as Completed (if ACCEPTED).
  - "Sent Requests": Lists outgoing requests and their statuses, with option to Mark as Completed (if ACCEPTED).

## Verification Plan

### Automated Tests
Currently, there seem to be no comprehensive automated service tests, only a default start test and maybe some smoke tests (`DbSmokeTest Runner` from earlier chats). I can add backend unit tests for `ExchangeRequestService` to verify the logic.
- We will create `ExchangeRequestServiceTest` mapping to the 10 scenarios in the user story (duplicate prevention, self-request prevention, status updates, owner authorization).

### Manual Verification
1. Run the Spring Boot application locally.
2. Login with User A (or register).
3. Create a Skill for User A.
4. Login with User B.
5. Browse skills, find User A's skill, and request an exchange with a message.
6. Verify duplicate requests are blocked.
7. Login with User A, navigate to "My Requests", and accept the request.
8. Login with User B, check "My Requests" to see the "ACCEPTED" status.
9. Verify unauthorized users cannot process requests they don't own.
10. Login with User B or User A, find the ACCEPTED request, and click "Mark as Completed".
11. Verify the status updates to COMPLETED and cannot be completed again.
